04030nam a22006615i 9780674258143DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222004mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742581437 a10.4159/97806742581432doi  a(DE-B1597)589287  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aGN495.6b.B77 2004 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a305.82221 aBrubaker, Rogers, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEthnicity without Groups /cRogers Brubaker. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Ethnicity without Groups -- t2 Beyond “Identity” -- t3 Ethnicity as Cognition -- t4 Ethnic and Nationalist Violence -- t5 The Return of Assimilation? -- t6 “Civic” and “Ethnic” Nationalism -- t7 Ethnicity, Migration, and Statehood in Post–Cold War Europe -- t8 1848 in 1998: The Politics of Commemoration in Hungary, Romania, and Slovakia -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Despite a quarter-century of constructivist theorizing in the social sciences and humanities, ethnic groups continue to be conceived as entities and cast as actors. Journalists, policymakers, and researchers routinely frame accounts of ethnic, racial, and national conflict as the struggles of internally homogeneous, externally bounded ethnic groups, races, and nations. In doing so, they unwittingly adopt the language of participants in such struggles, and contribute to the reification of ethnic groups. In this timely and provocative volume, Rogers Brubaker—well known for his work on immigration, citizenship, and nationalism—challenges this pervasive and commonsense “groupism.” But he does not simply revert to standard constructivist tropes about the fluidity and multiplicity of identity. Once a bracing challenge to conventional wisdom, constructivism has grown complacent, even cliched. That ethnicity is constructed is commonplace; this volume provides new insights into how it is constructed. By shifting the analytical focus from identity to identifications, from groups as entities to group-making projects, from shared culture to categorization, from substance to process, Brubaker shows that ethnicity, race, and nation are not things in the world but perspectives on the world: ways of seeing, interpreting, and representing the social world."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAssimilation (Sociology). 0aCognition and culture. 0aEthnic conflict. 0aEthnicity. 0aNationalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674258143zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674258143423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674258143/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK